4 A BILL FOR AN ACT ENTITLED: “AN ACT REVISING THE DECENNIAL VETERANS' LONG-TERM CARE
5 NEEDS STUDY; MOVING PRIMARY RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE SURVEY FROM THE DEPARTMENT OF
6 PUBLIC HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES TO THE MONTANA VETERANS' AFFAIRS DIVISION;
7 REQUIRING THE INVOLVEMENT OF STAKEHOLDERS; REQUIRING THE PREPARATION OF A STUDY
8 PLAN AND BUDGET ESTIMATE; REVISING REPORTING REQUIREMENTS; AND AMENDING SECTIONS
9 10-2-901, 10-2-902, AND 10-2-903, MCA.”
10
11 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF THE STATE OF MONTANA:
12
13 Section 1. Section 10-2-901, MCA, is amended to read:
14 "10-2-901. Decennial veterans' long-term care needs study. (1) On receipt of the most recent
15 federal census data, the department of public health and human services Montana veterans' affairs division, in
16 consultation with the Montana veterans' affairs division department of public health and human services, shall
17 perform an analysis of the long-term care needs of veterans in the state, known as the decennial veterans'
18 long-term care needs study.
19 (2) The study must determine the demographics of the Montana veteran population, including the
20 number and age of veterans in each county and the type of long-term care needs of the population. The long-
21 term care assessment for veterans study must also include evaluation of the need for nursing home,
22 domiciliary, and Alzheimer's disease support services, as well as the various types of community and in-home
23 care that are needed any other care needs identified by the Montana veterans' affairs division and by
24 stakeholders.
25 (3) The study must include a personal survey of the Montana veteran population, including online
26 and paper options and focus groups.
27 (4) This study must be conducted in collaboration with stakeholders, including but not limited to
28 veterans' outreach organizations, legislators, caregivers, and other local groups that work directly with the
